external_knowledge:
- "composition" refers to a musical piece;
- "notes" are the musical sounds within a composition;
- "time signature" defines the rhythm and meter of the music;
- "access date" and "access type" refer to when and how a composition was accessed in the system.

- `track_id = 1` refers to the first track in the composition;
- `prev_channel_id = 1` indicates the transition from the first channel to another;
- `onset_sec` is the start time of the note in seconds;
- `duration_sec` is the length of the note in seconds;
- `pitch` is the musical pitch of the note;
- `velocity` is the intensity or volume of the note;
- `channel_name` is the name of the channel where the note was played;
- `composition_name` is the name of the composition the note belongs to;
- `onset_diff` is the time difference between the current note and the previous note in seconds.

- Note types include quarter notes, half notes, etc.;
- Onset time is the time in seconds when the note starts;
- Velocity represents the intensity or volume of the note;
- Beat indicates the position of the note in the musical measure;
- Tempo is measured in beats per minute (BPM);
- Time signature describes the rhythmic structure of the music.

- "highest tempos" refers to the top 3 maximum tempos among all tracks within a composition;
- "tracks" are musical segments of a composition;
- "tempo" is the speed or pace of a piece of music, measured in beats per minute (BPM).

sql:
SELECT AVG(duration_sec) AS average_duration
FROM notes
WHERE track_id IN (SELECT track_id FROM tracks WHERE composition_id = 1);

